DTE ELECTRIC COMPANY FERC ELECTRIC TARIFF VOLUME No. 4
SCHEDULE A NEGOTIATED CAPACITY AND ENERGY
1. Duration
1.1 This schedule shall continue in effect throughout the duration of the Tariff of which it is a part, unless and until changed pursuant to the Tariff.
2. Services To Be Rendered
2.1 Capacity and Energy may be purchased by Customer from Company for the purpose of obtaining a supply of Capacity, Energy or both during the period covered by a commitment and includes negotiable degrees of firmness, variable charges and variable time duration. Company and Customer may also negotiate a Diversity Exchange.
2.2 Customer may reserve such Capacity as Company may have and is willing to make available or may arrange a Diversity Exchange. Company and Customer shall agree on the number of megawatts, charges, security arrangements and period of any transaction.
2.3 The degree of firmness shall be mutually agreed upon by both parties at the time the Capacity is reserved.
2.4 Any request or any acknowledgment of such request that may be given orally initially shall be confirmed in writing by Company or Customer prior to the commencement of a transaction.
2.5 During or in advance of the period that Capacity has been reserved or Energy is to be delivered to Customer, it shall be the responsibility of Customer to schedule the deliveries of Energy associated therewith in accordance with Subsection 6.2 of the Tariff. The Company has the responsibility to provide such Energy, pursuant to the degree of firmness established in Section 2.3, in amounts up to the number of megawatts reserved. Arrangements for the reservation of Capacity or Diversity Exchange including amount, price, firmness, term and security arrangements, if any, shall be specified in writing.
3. Compensation
3.1 Compensation for the supply and delivery of Capacity, Energy or both shall be no greater than the sum of the following rates:
3.1.1 Capacity supplied by Company:
a. At the rate of up to $681,470 per megawatt reserved per year ("demand charge")
b. At the rate of up to $56,789 per megawatt reserved per month year ("demand charge"), or
c. At the rate of up to $13,105 per megawatt reserved per week year ("demand charge"), or
d. At the rate of up to $2,184 per megawatt reserved per day year ("demand charge"), subject to the limitation that the total demand charge in any consecutive seven-day period shall not exceed the product of the highest number of megawatts of Capacity reserved on any day in the seven-day period, and $13,105, or
e. At the rate of up to $137 per megawatt reserved per hour year ("demand charge") subject to the limitation that the total demand charge in any consecutive seven-day period shall not exceed the product of the highest number of megawatts of Capacity reserved in any hour in the seven-day period, and $13,105. In addition, the total demand charge in any day shall not exceed the product of the highest number of megawatts of Capacity reserved in any hour in the day, and $2,184.
3.1.2 Energy Charge:
3.1.2.1 For Energy generated by Company: The Energy charge per megawatthour delivered is up to 110 % of Company's actual Out-of-Pocket Cost (OPC) of supplying Energy called for during such period.
3.1.2.2 For Energy purchased from a third party to supply Energy called for during such period:
a. The amount paid by Company, plus
b. The cost of transmission losses and any applicable taxes.
3.1.3 Plus any Third Party transmission service charges unless Customer is paying for such charges separate from this Tariff.
3.2 The rates established in subsections 3.1 notwithstanding, for each specific reservation of Capacity and Energy made pursuant to subsection 2.2 of this Power Sales Schedule, the sum of the demand and Energy charges shall not exceed the total of (a) the product of the number of megawatts reserved for such reservation times the maximum demand charge specified in subsection 3.1 above, and (b) the product of the number of megawatthours delivered under such reservation times 100% of the average cost per megawatthour of Energy generated by Fermi 2 for the second preceding month, but in no event shall such total be less than 100% of the total out-of-pocket cost of supplying the Capacity and Energy for such reservation.
3.3 The total Capacity of all sales by the Company under this Wholesale Power Sales Schedule, for which the demand charge is based on the cost of Fermi 2, is limited to 1100 MW in any hour. This limitation shall not preclude sales in excess of 1100 MW, rather it only restricts the volume of sales made under the demand charges contained in subsection 3.1 hereof. The Company may supply such amounts of power as it is able to market under this Wholesale Power Sales Schedule A, without limit, provided that the demand charges for amounts exceeding 1100 MW shall not exceed the following rate:
a. At the rate of up to $276,040 per megawatt reserved per year ("demand charge")
b. At the rate of up to $23,003 per megawatt reserved per month ("demand charge")
c. At the rate of up to $5,308 per megawatt reserved per week ("demand charge")
d. At the rate of up to $885 per megawatt reserved per day ("demand charge"), subject to the limitation that the total demand charge in any consecutive seven-day period shall not exceed the product of the highest number of megawatts of Capacity reserved on any day in the seven-day period, and $5,308, or
e. At the rate of up to $55 per megawatt reserved per hour ("demand charge"), subject to the limitation that the total demand charge in any consecutive seven-day period shall not exceed the product of the highest number of megawatts of Capacity reserved in any hour in the seven-day period, and $5,308. In addition, the total demand charge in any day shall not exceed the product of the highest number of megawatts of Capacity reserved in any hour of the day, and $885.
f. Sales made pursuant to the rates in this section are subject to the general provisions of this Power Sales Schedule, including subsection 2.3. Energy charges will be in accordance with subsection 3.1.2; however, the limit on total charges contained in Section 3.2 applies only to sales made pursuant to subsection 3.1.1. Transmission charges shall be in accordance with subsection 3.1.3.
3.4 Customer Supplied Fuel: At Customer's request, but subject to Company's agreement, Customer may supply fuel to Company in exchange for Capacity and associated Energy. When Customer supplies the fuel, Company will zero out the fuel cost in its calculation of Out-of-Pocket Cost for Energy and will use the heat rates of those units providing such Service to determine the amount of fuel delivered by the customer. In no event, shall the total compensation to Company (which shall include the agreed value of the fuel) exceed the cumulative rate caps for Capacity and Energy set out in Sections 3.1.1 and 3.1.2, as appropriate.
3.5 Type of Exchange: At the time a Diversity Exchange is agreed to, Company and Customer shall agree on the type of exchange as one of the following: (a) megawatt for megawatt, (b) megawatthour for megawatthour, (c) equal to the current efficiency of Ludington Pumped Storage Facility, which shall be the annual ratio of generation exclusive of plant use (kWh) to energy used for pumping (kWh), from the most recent Form 1 of Company (page 409, column (c), line 9 divided by line 10), or (d) up to the Capacity Charges specified in section 3.1 and energy is returned in kind.
3.6 Fixed rate per megawatthour: Company and Customer may agree to fixed rates per megawatthour for the term of an individual transaction provided, however, in no case shall the compensation, over the term of the transaction, exceed the cumulative rate caps for Capacity and Energy set out in sections 3.1.1 and 3.1.2, as appropriate.
3.7 On an annual basis, the Company will credit its FERC fuel adjustment clause (FAC) with at least enough revenue from its off-system sales revenues to offset the incremental costs which flow through the FAC resulting from all sales under this Tariff. If the sum of off-system sales revenues from the above sales is less than the sum of the above credits to the FAC, the Company will not include such difference in its cost of service for its next FERC base rate case.

DTE ELECTRIC COMPANY FERC ELECTRIC TARIFF VOLUME No. 4
SCHEDULE B RESALE TRANSMISSION SERVICES
1. Duration
1.1 This schedule shall continue in effect throughout the duration of the Tariff of which it is a part, unless and until changed pursuant to the Tariff.
2. Services To Be Rendered
2.1 The Company may sell, assign, or transfer to the Customer all or a portion of the Company's rights to the use of the transmission system of a transmission provider that the Company has reserved for its own use under a service agreement with the transmission provider, or has acquired from another customer of the transmission provider.
3. Eligibility
3.1 In order to be eligible for resale transmission services, the Customer must be an Eligible Customer as that term is defined in the Transmission Tariff of the transmission provider from whom the transmission service to be transferred was originally obtained.
4. Terms and Conditions of Service
4.1 Except as to the price, the terms and conditions under which the Company will resell transmission rights to the Customer will be the terms and conditions governing the original grant of transmission service rights by the transmission provider.
4.2 The curtailment priority of transmission service resold under this section of the Tariff will be consistent with the Transmission Tariff pursuant to which the Company obtained the transmission service being resold, provided that the Company may resell as non-firm point-to-point transmission service capacity that it purchased on a firm point-to-point basis.
5. Compensation
5.1 The Company will sell transmission rights to the Customer at a price not to exceed the highest of (a) the original price paid by the Company; (b) the applicable transmission provider's maximum rate on file at the time of the sale to the Customer for service of the same duration; or (3) the Company's own opportunity costs, capped at the applicable transmission provider's cost of expansion at the time of the Company's sale of the transmission rights to the Customer.
5.2 The Company will not recover opportunity costs on an incremental basis in connection with the resale of transmission rights without first receiving Commission approval pursuant to a filing under Section 205 of the Federal Power Act.
6. Records
6.1 The Company will keep such records as may be needed to provide a clear history of all resales of transmission capacity under this schedule that the Company has reserved or acquired for its own use on the transmission systems of other transmission providers. The Company will retain the original copies of all such records.

FERC ELECTRIC TARIFF VOLUME No. 4
COST BASED RATES (WPS-1)
DTE ELECTRIC COMPANY FERC ELECTRIC TARIFF VOLUME No. 4 COST BASED RATES (WPS-1)
1. Preamble
The Company offers to sell Capacity and Energy from time to time in accordance with and subject to the terms and conditions contained in this Tariff when Company and a Customer agree on specific Transaction(s).
2. Definitions
2.1 "Capacity" means the resource that produces electric Energy measured in megawatts.
2.2 "Company" means DTE Electric Company.
2.3 "Commission" or "FERC" means the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission or any successor federal agency having regulatory jurisdiction over this Tariff.
2.4 "Customer" means any person engaged in the wholesale sale of electric Energy for resale for which Company has entered into a Service Agreement for providing service to such person under this Tariff and who can prove and maintain its creditworthiness to the Company and shall not include ultimate consumers of electric Energy.
2.5 "Day" means a twenty-four hour period commencing at twelve o'clock midnight prevailing Eastern Standard Time and ending at the next following twelve o'clock midnight.
2.6 "Diversity Exchange" means the exchange of Capacity and Energy in one period for Capacity and Energy in another period.
2.7 "Energy" means electric Energy delivered under this Tariff at three-phase, 60-hertz and measured in megawatt hours.
2.8 "Force Majeure" means earthquake, storm, lightning, flood, backwater caused by flood, fire, explosion, act of the public enemy, epidemic, accident, failure of facilities, equipment or fuel supply, acts of God, war, riot, civil disturbances, strike, labor disturbances, labor or material shortage, national emergency, restraint by court order or other public authority or governmental agency, interruption of synchronous operation, or other similar or dissimilar causes beyond the control of the Party affected which causes such Party could not have avoided by exercising Prudent Utility Practice. Nothing contained herein shall be construed to require a party to settle any strike, lockout, work stoppage or other industrial disturbance or dispute in which it may be involved or to take an appeal from any judicial, regulatory or administrative action.
2.9 "Hour" shall mean any clock hour.
2.10 "Month" means all of the days in any calendar month, or if a reservation starts on any day other than the first day of the month, the number of days in the month in which the reservation commences.
2.11 "Off-Peak" means any hour not falling within the On-Peak period.
2.12 "On-Peak" means any hour during the period starting 7:00 a.m. and ending 11:00 p.m. prevailing Eastern Standard Time of each day except all hours on Sunday and the days on which the following holidays are generally observed: New Year's Day, Memorial Day, Independence Day, Labor Day, Thanksgiving Day and Christmas Day
2.13 "Out-of-Pocket Costs" (OPC) as it applies to Transactions arranged pursuant to this Tariff, shall mean all expenses incurred by the Company that would not otherwise have been incurred if the Transaction had not been arranged. Such expenses will include, but are not limited to, costs associated with fuel, variable operation, variable maintenance, startup, shutdown, minimum run, taxes, minimum load, SO2 and other emission allowances, transmission losses, charges for any Capacity and Energy purchased or charges of a similar or dissimilar nature, which is reasonably allocated by the Company to such a Transaction. In no event shall such costs include charges for transmission services provided by the Company.
2.14 "Party" or "Parties" means either the Company or Customer that has executed a Service Agreement under this Tariff.
2.15 "Prudent Utility Practice" means any of the practice, methods and acts engaged in or approved by a significant portion of the electric utility industry during the relevant time period, or any of the practices, methods and acts which, in the exercise of reasonable judgment in the light of the facts known at the time the decision was made, could have been expected to accomplish the desired result at a reasonable cost consistent with good business practices, reliability, safety and expedition. Prudent Utility Practice is not intended to be limited to the optimum practice, method or act to the exclusion of all others, but rather to be a spectrum of acceptable practices, methods or acts.
2.16 "Receiving Party" means, unless otherwise agreed, an entity other than the Customer receiving at a point of delivery the Energy purchased under this Tariff. Unless otherwise agreed, a Receiving Party must be directly connected to the Company's transmission system and may not, in any case, be a retail Customer of the Company, either in whole or in part.
2.17 "Services" is that specified in the Wholesale Power Sales Schedule A.
2.18 "Service Agreement" means the initial agreement and any amendments or supplements thereto, entered into by Customer and Company under the Tariff.
2.19 "Third Party" means any Electric Utility not designated as "Company" or "Customer" for the purpose of this Tariff.
2.20 "Transaction" means the supply of Capacity, Energy or both by the Company to the Customer under the rates and charges in this Tariff and Wholesale Power Sales Schedule A.
2.21 "Week" means any seven consecutive days.
2.22 "Year" means any twelve month period ending at 12 o'clock midnight on the eve of the one-year anniversary of its starting date.
2.23 "Transmission Tariff" means that document describing the rates, terms and conditions under which transmission service will be provided.
3. Purchase and Sale Requirements
The Company will sell Capacity, Energy or both under this Tariff when Company and Customer have reached agreement on the rates, terms and conditions for a specific Transaction. Such rates, terms and conditions shall be in conformance with any requirements of this Tariff.
In order for a Customer to take service under this Tariff, a Service Agreement must be executed by Company and the Customer
4. Creditworthiness
For the purpose of determining the ability of the Customer to meet its obligations related to service hereunder, the Company may require reasonable credit review procedures. This review shall be made in accordance with standard commercial practices. In addition, the Company may require the Customer to provide and maintain in effect during the term of the Service Agreement and any Transaction, unconditional and irrevocable letter(s) of credit in an amount consistent with the Transaction as security to meet its responsibilities and obligations under this Tariff, or an alternative form of security proposed by the Customer and acceptable to Company and consistent with commercial practices that protects the Company against the risk of non-payment. The Company may also require security or additional security during a Transaction based on changed circumstances.
5. Services to be Rendered
Company may offer to sell Capacity and Energy subject to the rates, terms and conditions set forth in the attached Wholesale Power Sales Schedule A.
6. General Terms and Conditions
6.1 Delivery Arrangements.
All Services provided hereunder will be scheduled and made through a point(s) of delivery designated by Company and Customer for the particular Transaction at the time the Transaction is scheduled or as otherwise mutually agreed upon.
6.2 Scheduling.
All Services provided hereunder shall be delivered and billed on a scheduled basis in accordance with the applicable schedule and the agreed upon terms and conditions of a particular Transaction. The minimum scheduled amount in any hour for any Transaction will not be less than one (1) MW.
Company and Customer agree on all schedules for the delivery of Energy under this Tariff. The Company will accommodate requested schedule changes at its discretion.
Company and Customer shall designate to the other in writing the persons authorized to transact on its behalf hereunder and the telephone and facsimile numbers which shall be employed for communications hereunder.
6.3 Transmission Service Arrangements.
Delivery of the Services under this Tariff will be under the rates, terms and conditions contained in any applicable Transmission Tariff.
Either the Company or Customer may arrange for such transmission service. Unless otherwise agreed, the Party arranging for such transmission service will assume full responsibility for that service.
6.3.1 Customer Arranges Third Party Transmission
Unless otherwise agreed between Company and Customer, claims or demands made by other utilities arising out of a Transaction hereunder with respect to the claimed use of the transmission systems of such other utilities shall be the sole responsibility of Customer.
The Party procuring transmission service will be responsible for ensuring the necessary coordination among all Parties to a Transaction.
6.4 Billing.
As soon as practicable, after the end of each billing period, Company shall render to Customer a bill for all charges due from Customer for Capacity and Energy provided in such billing period under this Tariff. All amounts owed by Customer to the Company shall be due and payable on the tenth (10) day following receipt of a bill or on the first working day thereafter if the payment day falls on other than a working day. Interest on unpaid amounts shall accrue at the rate of two percent (2%) per annum above the prime commercial lending rate established from time to time by Chase Manhattan Bank, N. A., New York, New York, from the date due until the date upon which payment is made. Unless otherwise agreed upon, a calendar month shall be the standard billing period.
All payments to Company shall be wire transferred to a DTE Electric Company bank account designated by Company in writing to the Customer.
All questions concerning the billings and payments of invoices under this Tariff shall be directed to:
Settlements Supervisor 414 S. Main Street, Suite 200 Ann Arbor, Michigan 48104
6.5 Billing Disputes.
In the event the Customer wishes to contest a portion of a billed amount, the Customer shall pay the portion not contested, and interest shall accrue on the unpaid portion while resolution of contested amounts is pending.
6.6 Liability.
Neither the Company nor Customer shall be liable to the other for any consequential, incidental, punitive or other special damages relating to the performance or nonperformance of this Tariff or any Transaction hereunder.
Customer shall remain liable to Company for demand charges associated with Transactions regardless of any interruption except in such instances where it is Company's generation system which is the cause of the interruption, or unless otherwise agreed. In circumstances where the interruption occurs on Company's generation system, compensation for demand charges shall be adjusted as specified in Wholesale Power Sales Schedule A attached hereto, or unless otherwise agreed, as the Customer's sole and exclusive remedy.
6.7 Limitation of Liability
Unless otherwise agreed, the Company's liability to the Customer related to or arising out of this Tariff or any Transaction hereunder (whether based on contract, tort or negligence, strictly liability or otherwise) shall not exceed the demand charges paid by the Customer for Services during the reservation period for the Transaction under which the claim arose.
6.8 Exclusion of Third Party Beneficiaries
No other entity is intended to be a third party beneficiary under this Tariff.
6.9 Force Majeure.
Any Party rendered unable to fulfill any of its obligations under this Tariff or Transaction by reason of Force Majeure shall exercise Prudent Utility Practice to remove such inability with all reasonable dispatch. In the event of a Force Majeure, the non-affected Party shall have the immediate right to terminate any Transaction impeded or affected by the Force Majeure upon two (2) hours written notice. In the event any Party is unable, in whole or in part, to perform any of its obligations by reason of Force Majeure, and the non-affected Party has not terminated any Transaction impeded or affected by the Force Majeure, then the obligations of the Party relying thereon, insofar as such obligations are affected by such Force Majeure, shall be suspended during the continuance thereof but no longer. Any Transaction or portion thereof suspended shall not be made up unless mutually agreed. The Party invoking the Force Majeure shall specifically state the full particulars of the Force Majeure and the time and date when the Force Majeure occurred. Notices given under the provisions of this section shall be confirmed in writing as soon as reasonably possible. When the Force Majeure ceases, the Party relying thereon shall give immediate notice thereof to the other Parties. This Tariff shall remain in full force and effect, even if a specific transaction is terminated due to a Force Majeure.
6.10 Indemnity
For the purpose of this Section 6.10, the term "Party" shall include each Party's directors, officers, employees, and agents. To the extent permitted by law, each Party shall indemnify, save harmless, and defend the other Party from and against any loss, liability, costs, expenses, suits, actions, claims and all other obligations arising out of injuries to persons or damage to property caused by or in any way attributable to the ownership or operation of its own facilities, except that portion of any liabilities that arise out of the other Party's contributing negligent acts or omissions.
6.11 Records
For a period of seven years, Company and Customer shall maintain written transaction records consisting of, but not limited to, Capacity reserved, Energy scheduled, commitment time, transaction times and transaction pricing. Company and Customer shall make such records available for inspection and audit by the other party at reasonable times and places at the other party's request.
6.12 Assignment
The Company can assign rights and obligations without consent of the Customer. The Customer can assign rights and obligations only with written consent of Company which will not unreasonably be withheld. In the event of such assignment, any such assignee shall be required to assume all of the obligations of the assignor under this Tariff and any Transaction thereunder pursuant to a written agreement. In any event, customer shall remain secondarily liable for all obligations.
6.13 Notices
All notices and requests under this Tariff shall be in writing and shall be delivered in person, or sent by first class mail, or electronic facsimile transmission addressed to the Party to be served at such address as the Parties may designate in writing from time to time.
6.14 Regulation
This Tariff shall be subject to the jurisdiction of any governmental regulatory authority or authorities having jurisdiction over the parties and the subject matter thereof.
6.15 Effective Date
Service provided under the Tariff shall become effective on the date specified in the Service Agreement.
7. Default and Remedies
The Company shall be in default if it fails to deliver the Services designated in any Transaction for three (3) consecutive days unless otherwise agreed. Upon such default, unless otherwise agreed, the Customer's sole and exclusive remedy will be to cancel any Transaction upon two (2) hours written notice and receive a refund of any demand charges paid associated with any Transactions hereunder.
The Customer shall be in default if it fails to take the Energy designated in any Transaction. The Customer will pay for all Services provided and will be responsible for all demand charges associated with such services.
The Customer shall be in default if the Company requests and the Customer fails to provide adequate security as described in Section 4 of this Tariff. Company shall have the right to suspend an existing Capacity and/or Energy Transaction and cancel the Service Agreement.
In the event the Customer fails to make full payment of any undisputed portion of a bill rendered under this Tariff on or before the due date, Company will notify the Customer of such delinquency and the Customer will have fifteen days from the date of mailing (as determined by postmark) or fax of such notice to cure its delinquency. In the event that the Customer fails to make full payment of the delinquent amount (including interest accrued at the interest rate as specified in Section 6.4 herein) within such fifteen day period, Company shall have the right to suspend an existing Capacity and/or Energy Transaction and cancel the Service Agreement. Company shall cease curtailment under this provision if and when the Customer corrects the delinquency.
8. Non-Waiver of Defaults
No waiver by any Party of any default of the other Party under this Tariff shall operate as a waiver of a future default whether of a like or different character.
9. Changes in Rates, Charges, Classifications, Service, Rules, Regulations or Service Agreements
The provision of service by Company under this Tariff or the Wholesale Power Sales Schedule A attached to this Tariff, and any Service Agreement are subject to the jurisdiction of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission. Nothing contained in this Tariff or any Service Agreement entered into hereunder shall be construed as affecting or limiting in any way the right of Company unilaterally to file with the Commission, or make application to the Commission for, changes in rates, charges, classifications, or service, or any rule or regulation relating thereto, in this Tariff, the attached Wholesale Power Sales Schedule A or Service Agreement under Section 205 of the Federal Power Act pursuant to the Commission's rules and regulations promulgated thereunder, or under other applicable statutes or regulations.
10. Governing Law
The formation validity, interpretation, execution, amendment and termination of this Agreement shall be governed by the laws of the State of Michigan and any actions with respect thereto may be brought only in a court of competent jurisdiction located in Wayne County, Michigan, if jurisdiction is not with the FERC.
11. Termination of Service Agreement
The Service Agreement (but not a Transaction) may be terminated by either Party upon sixty (60) days prior written notice. The Service Agreement will remain in effect until all Transactions previously agreed upon or entered into are completed.
12. After Termination or Cancellation
The applicable provisions of this Tariff including indemnity and any Service Agreement entered into under this Tariff shall continue in effect after termination or cancellation thereof to the extent necessary to provide for final billing, billing adjustments and payments.
13. Resale of Transmission Rights
The Company may sell, assign, or transfer to the Customer all or a portion of the Company's rights to the use of the transmission system of a transmission provider that the Company has reserved for its own use under a service agreement with the transmission provider. The price, terms, and conditions of such transmission resale service shall be as set forth in Schedule B to this Power Sales Agreement.

record_data.record_narrative_name: Renaissance Power Plant Reactive Revenue Requirement
record_data.record_plain_text:
Reactive Supply and Voltage Control from Generation Sources Service DTE Electric Company (Seller) provides Reactive Supply and Voltage Control from Generation Sources Service (Reactive Service) from the Renaissance Power Plant, a natural gas-fired peaking generating facility located in Montcalm County, Michigan (Generation Facility) that is interconnected to the transmission system owned by the Michigan Electric Transmission Company, LLC (METC) in order to assist in maintaining transmission voltages within acceptable limits on the Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. (MISO) system. This tariff sets forth Seller's revenue requirements for the provision of Reactive Service from Generation Facility to METC consistent with Schedule 2 of the MISO Tariff. Seller's revenue requirement consists of the sum of the charges for the following: (1) The Fixed Capability Revenue Requirement; and (2) Lost Opportunity Costs. This Rate Schedule shall be effective upon the date authorized by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission. REVENUE REQUIREMENT:
1) FIXED CAPABILITY COMPONENT
The annual revenue requirement for the Fixed Capability Component is $881,000. The monthly charge is $73,416.67.
2) LOST OPPORTUNITY COST COMPONENT
Seller may receive revenues for Lost Opportunity Costs in an amount equal to the costs, if any, it incurs as a result of lowering its MW output, which costs shall include the actual incremental fuel and operation and maintenance expense Seller incurs plus an amount equal to the costs, if any, Seller incurs for any emissions impacts as a result of lowering its MW output, not otherwise included in section (1) of this tariff plus any additional out-of-pockets costs or expenses actually incurred or other substantiated amount necessary to keep Seller whole with regard to the MWs not generated or MW sales foregone, including demonstrable lost opportunity costs. In the event that Seller incurs such Lost Opportunity Costs, Seller shall make a filing with the Commission to substantiate such costs.
NOTICE PROVISIONS:
1) SUSPENSION
In connection with the change in ownership of the Generation Facility from Renaissance Power, L.L.C. (Renaissance) to Seller, the collection of the annual revenue requirement shall be suspended effective January 21, 2015.
2) REINSTATEMENT
The collection of the annual revenue requirement shall be reinstated effective on the first day of the month immediately following consummation of the transfer of this Rate Schedule from Renaissance to Seller or the first day of the month if such transfer occurs on the first day of the month (Reinstatement Effective Date). Seller shall provide MISO notice of the date of the Commission authorization within five (5) business days of the date of such authorization (Reinstatement Notice). The Reinstatement Notice shall state the date of the Commission authorization and Reinstatement Effective Date and shall include a copy of the Commission order authorizing the transfer.

DTE ELECTRIC COMPANY FERC ELECTRIC TARIFF VOLUME No. 7 Reactive Supply and Voltage Control from Generating Resources Service
DTE Electric Company provides Reactive Supply and Voltage Control from Generation Resources Service ("Reactive Supply Service") from its facility located in Township of East China, Michigan ("Dean Facility"), which is interconnected with the International Transmission Company ("ITC') Transmission system and under the operational control of the Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. ("MISO"). This FERC Electric Tariff Volume No. 7 sets forth the revenue requirement for the provision of Reactive Supply Service from its Dean Facility to the MISO. Payments from the MISO shall be in accordance with Schedule 2 of the MISO's Open Access Transmission Tariff.
DTE Electric Company's annual and monthly revenue requirements for the Dean Facility are set forth below:
ANNUAL REVENUE REQUIREMENT: $ 980,000

DTE ELECTRIC COMPANY FERC ELECTRIC TARIFF VOLUME No. 5 Reactive Supply and Voltage Control from Generation Sources Service
DTE Electric Company ("DTE") provides Reactive Supply and Voltage Control from Generation Sources Service ("Reactive Supply") to the Midcontinent Independent Transmission System Operator, Inc. ("MISO"). This Tariff sets forth DTE's revenue requirement for the provision of Reactive Supply to the MISO. DTE shall receive payment for Reactive Supply directly from the MISO in accordance with Schedule 2 of the MISO's transmission tariff. DTE's annual revenue requirement is:

DTE ELECTRIC COMPANY FERC ELECTRIC TARIFF VOLUME No. 3 MARKET BASED RATES (WPS-2)
1.0. Definitions The following items shall have the specified meaning when used in this Tariff or in a Service Agreement: 1.1 Commission: The Federal Energy Regulatory Commission. 1.2 Customer: An entity that executes a Service Agreement under this Tariff. 1.3 Seller: DTE Electric Company (DTE). 1.4 Service Agreement: The initial agreement and any supplements thereto entered into by a Customer and DTE for service under this Tariff. 1.5 Tariff: This Wholesale Power Sales tariff as it may be amended and/or superseded from time to time. 1.6 Transaction: An individual transaction scheduled pursuant to this Tariff and a Service Agreement. 2.0. Availability 2.1. This Tariff is available for purchases of electric energy, capacity, and/or ancillary services from DTE. 3.0. Character of Service 3.1. General DTE may provide capacity, energy, and/or ancillary services under this Tariff in varying amounts, at varying levels of firmness or priorities of service, for varying periods of service, and in accordance with varying delivery schedules, as agreed to between the Customer and DTE. 3.2. Ancillary Services 3.2.1. RTO/ISO: MISO: Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. (MISO) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to MISO.
3.2.2. Third Party Provider:
Third-party ancillary services: Seller offers Regulation and Frequency Response Service, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service, Energy and Generator Imbalance Service, Operating Reserve-Spinning, and Operating Reserve-Supplemental. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; and (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier. Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating Reserve-Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization. Sales of Regulation and Frequency Response Service and Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except at rates not to exceed the buying public utility transmission provider's OATT rate for the same service or where the Commission has granted authorization.
4.0 Seller Category
Seller is a Category 2 seller in the Central Region, as defined in 18 CFR Section; 35.36(a). Seller is a Category 1 seller in the Northeast Region, Southeast Region, Southwest Power Pool Region, Southwest Region, and Northwest Region, as defined in 18 CFR Section; 35.36(a).
5.0 Rates
The rates for purchases under this Tariff shall be as agreed to by the Customer and DTE. 6.0 Service Agreements 6.1 Prior to the commencement of service to a new customer, DTE and each new Customer will execute a Service Agreement. 6.2 DTE may refuse, at its sole discretion, to enter into a Service Agreement or Transaction under this Tariff. DTE is under no obligation to execute a Service Agreement to provide service hereunder. Acceptance of service by the Customer pursuant to a Service Agreement commits the Customer to the provisions of this Tariff and to the terms of the Service Agreement. 7.0 Expansion of Facilities DTE will have no obligation under this Tariff or any Service Agreement executed hereunder to plan its system or to enlarge or modify its facilities in order to provide or maintain energy and/or capacity sold hereunder. 8.0 Revisions to Tariff DTE may file revisions to this Tariff with the Commission. Nothing contained in this Tariff shall be construed as affecting or limiting in any way the right of DTE to unilaterally file with the Commission for a change in any aspect of this Tariff under Section 205 or 206 of the Federal Power Act pursuant to the Commission's rules and Regulations promulgated thereunder. 9.0 Effective Date This Tariff shall be effective on the date established by the Commission. 10.0 Compliance with Commission Regulations Seller shall comply with the provisions of 18 CFR Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning seller's market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes seller to engage in affiliate sales under this tariff or otherwise restricts or limits the seller's market-based rate authority. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 CFR Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning seller's market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this tariff. 11.0 Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market-Based Rate Authority In The Detroit Edison Co., 95 FERC 61,240 (2001) and The Detroit Edison Co., Docket Nos. ER97-324-024, et al. (Feb. 16, 2012) (unpublished letter order): The Commission has waived its affiliate restrictions on sharing of market information and functional separation with respect to inter-affiliate transactions between Seller and DTE Energy Trading, Inc. No entity affiliated with DTE is eligible for service under this Tariff, except for DTE Energy Trading, Inc. The Commission authorized Seller to engage in affiliate power sales with DTE Energy Trading, Inc., under the terms of an existing transaction confirmation to a Master Power and Purchase Agreement that expires on June 1, 2023. See DTE Electric Co., 183 FERC 61, 097 (2023).
